      "bodyTr": "Foreign visitors to Korea in the first quarter of this year reached 4.76 million, marking an all-time high for the quarter. This represents a 23 percent increase from the same period last year. The Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism attributed this growth to the global popularity of Korean culture. The BTS concert at Gwanghwamun Plaza last month is believed to have played a significant role in driving these numbers.\n\nThe phenomenon of Korean culture serving as a driving force for Korea's tourism has become increasingly evident in recent years. A 2024 survey by the Korea Culture and Tourism Institute found that \"Korean Wave content\" was the top reason foreign tourists became interested in Korea, followed by \"traditional Korean culture.\" What is particularly encouraging is that this interest is expanding beyond Seoul to regions with diverse traditional cultural attractions.\n\nAccording to Ministry of Culture data, foreign tourists entering through provincial airports in the first quarter surged 50 percent compared to the same period last year. Many tourists using provincial airports are turning their attention to regional tourism. The regional visitation rate among foreign visitors in the first quarter stood at 34.5 percent, up 3 percentage points from a year earlier, while their regional stay duration and card spending within regions increased 36 percent and 27 percent respectively.\n\nWhile it may be premature to say that the nature of foreign tourism to Korea has fundamentally changed, it is certainly encouraging that foreigners are now venturing into regions, staying longer, and spending more. President Lee Jae-myung's mention at the State Council meeting on the 14th of mobilizing local residents, small business owners, and tourism activists while having government agencies support these efforts reflects an intention to nurture this trend.\n\nIn response, the Ministry of Interior and Safety has proposed establishing public-private tourism councils at the city, county, and district levels, and the Ministry of Culture has expressed its willingness to support regional tourism activists. The direction of public-private cooperation to actively utilize private sector ideas is sound. However, for this to translate into results, local government efficiency must be secured in addressing issues such as transportation, infrastructure, and regulations, and political logic that obstructs efficient decision-making must be excluded.\n\nTourism is one of the precious solutions that can help alleviate regional hollowing—currently one of Korea's most pressing issues—and the widening gap between the capital region and non-capital regions. We must seize the opportunity presented by the increase in visitors to Korea driven by Korean culture.",
